node.text:
Meet the kung fu master 👀

Mantids are born with excellent eyesight. However, their keen eyes are no equal match for that of a hungry jumping spider. But they do have one trick up their sleeve when it comes to self-defence: partaking in a bit of kung-fu. This self-defence mechanism serves to confuse its predator, making the insect appear bigger than it actually is. But, the fight to stay alive doesn’t end there…

The carnivorous blue whale (Balaenoptera musculus) can span up to 30m in length, and weigh over 180,000kg, making it the largest animal to have ever lived. Its tongue alone can weigh as much as some elephants. They cannot breathe underwater, and instead, pop up to inhale air though a blowhole on the top of their heads.

Meet the kung fu master 👀

Mantids are born with excellent eyesight. However, their keen eyes are no equal match for that of a hungry jumping spider. But they do have one trick up their sleeve when it comes to self-defence: partaking in a bit of kung-fu. This self-defence mechanism serves to confuse its predator, making the insect appear bigger than it actually is. But, the fight to stay alive doesn’t end there…
